<P>
NAVY ISOLATES DEFECT IN TRIDENT MISSILE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Navy has found the mechanical problem that caused a Trident 2 missile to 
explode last March, and corrective design changes will contribute to a 
three-month delay in deployment, a military official said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
Dan Howard, the Pentagon's chief spokesman, said a Navy board of inquiry had 
blamed the failure on a mechanical linkage in the first-stage nozzle. The 
Pentagon previously had disclosed preliminary findings, made final by the Navy 
board. 
</P>
<P>
"We now expect the first operational missiles to be at sea on the (submarine) 
USS Tennessee in March" of 1990, he said. 
</P>
<P>
The Navy's investigation began March 21, shortly after a Trident 2 missile 
fired from the Tennessee blew up four seconds after launch. 
</P>
