<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: NEWPORT BEACH; 
</P>
<P>
30 WILL LEAVE FOR JAPAN TO VISIT SISTER CITY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Thirty Newport Beach city officials and Rotary and Jaycee club members will 
leave for Okazaki, Japan, on Sunday to commemorate the 5th anniversary of 
Newport and Okazaki becoming sister cities and the 25th anniversary of the 
Okazaki South Rotary Club. 
</P>
<P>
The group represents the Newport Beach Sister City Assn. and will include 
former mayor Doreen Marshall, Building Director Ray Schuller, Jaycees' 
President Mark Cleary, Sister City President Wendell Fish and Miss Newport 
Beach Tanya Newbould. 
</P>
<P>
The group will tour Tokyo for three days and then attend the sister city 
programs May 11 to 15. 
</P>
<P>
The Newport Beach City Council adopted Okazaki as a sister city in 1984. 
Okazaki is about 200 miles southwest of Tokyo. The purpose of the program is to 
help promote greater international understanding and to develop direct 
association with foreign cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
