NATION; 
</P>
<P>
REHNQUIST URGES JUDGES PAY HIKE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist urged Congress today to give the nation's 
federal judges an immediate 30% pay raise. 
</P>
<P>
Calling inadequate salaries "the most serious threat to the future of the 
judiciary," Rehnquist sought support for legislation providing the raise and 
regular cost-of-living adjustments. 
</P>
<P>
"This is not, in my view, fairly termed a pay raise," Rehnquist said in a 
statement to the House Post Office and Civil Service Committee. "This is 
instead a partial recapture of the tremendous decline in purchasing power that 
has affected judicial salaries over the last 20 years." 
</P>
<P>
He said he recognizes that there was "widespread public opposition" to a 
defeated proposal for a much larger 51% pay raise for senior government 
officials, including members of Congress and federal judges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
