<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD; 
</P>
<P>
SOVIETS CONSIDER ALLOWING STRIKES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MOSCOW 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Soviet trade unions, long closely controlled by Communist authorities, will be 
given the right to strike under a draft law to be adopted in the next few 
months, union leader Stepan Shalayev said today. 
</P>
<P>
The draft law, which sets out a broad range of powers for unions, follows 
sporadic reports from across the country of wildcat strikes by miners, bus 
drivers and carpet weavers demanding better pay and conditions. 
</P>
<P>
"The right (to strike) is being considered as a means to press management to 
speed up the resolution of labor disputes," Shalayev said in an interview with 
the trade union daily Trud. "But it is an extreme measure which should be 
applied only in exceptional cases." He said work stoppages should "not be 
considered a normal phenomenon in our society." 
</P>
</TEXT>
